<strong>WORKS CITED</strong>
<br><br>
Add a &#8216;Works Cited&#8217; entry at the end of your essay citing all sources used in the body of your writing.
<br><br>
<strong>Format</strong>
<br><br>
If you are writing about a film or television series that does not focus on one particular individual&#8217;s contribution, begin the entry with the title followed by the contributor&#8217;s name and their descriptive label.
<br><br>
Films and television series or often produced and distributed by different companies. Cite the organisation that had primary responsibility for the work.
<br><br>
A description of the source can also be added, if clarity is needed, at the end of the Works Cited entry.
	<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent">
	<em>Title of Work</em>. Name(s) of contributors and descriptive label for each contributor, production or distribution company, year. Description.
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Example</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent">
	<em><span class="hover" class="hover" title="Title of Work">Outside the Lines</span></em>. 
	<span class="hover" title="Name(s) of Director(s)">Directed by Archie Smith</span>. 
	<span class="hover" title="Name(s) of Performer(s)">performance by Carrie Chan, Darryn Williams and Manu Tahatai</span>,
	<span class="hover" title="Production or distribution company">Upbeat Pictures</span>, 
	<span class="hover" title="year">2056</span>. 
	<span class="hover" title="Description">Film</span>.
</blockquote>
<br>
If you are citing the contribution of a particular individual (in this case the director), include their name in the author position followed by a descriptive label. 
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent">
	<span class="hover" title="Contributor&#8217;s name">Smith, Archie, director</span>. 
	<em><span class="hover" title="Title of Work">Outside the Lines</span></em>. 
	<span class="hover" title="Production or distribution company">Upbeat Pictures</span>, 
	<span class="hover" title="year">2056</span>. 
	<span class="hover" title="Description">Film</span>.
</blockquote>
