<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
When a work is listed by title in the Works Cited list, include the title of the work in italics within the sentence. 
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	<em>Outside the Lines</em> demonstrates&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
In a parenthetical citation, abbreviate the title if is longer than a noun phrase, immediately following the cited material. For example, <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Southern Novels</em> consists entirely of a noun phrase (a noun <em>Novels</em> preceded by two modifiers) and wouldnâ€™t be shortened. By contrast, <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels of the South</em> would be shortened to its noun phrase <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels</em>. The abbreviated title should begin with the word by which it is alphabetised in the Works Cited. If the title does not begin with a noun phrase, cite the first word if it is enough to direct the reader to the correct entry. For further information on abbreviating titles, see 3.2.1 in the <a href="http://west-sydney-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/UWS-ALMA:default_scope:UWS-ALMA21186157620001571" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">MLA Handbook (8th edition)</a>.
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;a sense of heightened emotion (<em>Outside</em>).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the Works Cited entry begins with the name of a contributor, use the contributor(s) name whenever you refer to the source in your writing. Descriptive labels (e.g. director) is not required in-text. 
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith demonstrates&hellip;
	<br><br>
	Or
	<br><br>
	&hellip;a sense of heightened emotion (Smith).
</blockquote>
<br>
Since page numbers cannot be given to direct your reader, when referring to a specific part of the film, describe the scene as accurately and concisely as possible.
